1. Linked List
A data structure that has nodes and pointers
- Each node has both data and pointer
  - the pointer directs the list to the next value in the list
A Circular linked list can be made by having the final pointer go back to the first value in the list
Can be through a STATIC array -> they are a fixed size and cannot be made larger/smaller
OR
Can be used through OOP
- Any available memory address can be used to store data

- Can be used by the operating system managing a processor
- image viewers
- music players
- web browsers
Can also be used as hash table collision overflow

2. Graphs
A data structure that has vertices and edges
each vertex can have more than 2 edges
- can either point in a direction (directed) or just a line (undirected)
Graphs can be weighted, with each edge given a value
^ required for things like dijkstras algorithm

3. Stacks
Items are 'pushed' onto the top of the stack, and are 'popped' from the top of the stack
